* ranking, **then** B's memories are boosted vs. A's.\n\n  Line 351: Today recall is FTS5 + semantic fallback at the global level. A per-project embedding\n\n  Line 380: ### G-K — Recall result explainer\n\n  Line 381: For each result, a one-line \"why this ranked here\" (FTS hit, semantic similarity,\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/skills/ContinuousLearning/HookIntegration.md:\n  Line 29: - **Scoped:** Top 15 memories for the current project, ranked by importance DESC\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:\n  Line 15: **Where we are (v1.4.20):** A working LTM plugin with SQLite + FTS5 + 4 hooks + 7 MCP tools + grouped commands. Functional. Honest weaknesses: silent hook failures, hand-rolled migrations, O(N) recall, no provenance, no audit, no observability. UX is invisible-by-default but onboarding is \"abandoned by 50%\".\n\n  Line 30: | Recall scoring at scale | — | W4 | C8 explainer | §8.3 S2 | TBD §4 (decay_score) |\n\n  Line 114: **Goal:** FTS5 stays. Embeddings become pluggable, not bundled.\n\n  Line 121: | Arch | C8 Recall result explainer — show why each result ranked where it did |\n\n  Line 125: **Exit criteria:** plugin works fully without any embedding provider · with provider, recall latency stays < 200ms p95 · explainer shows score breakdown.\n\n  Line 215: - Phase 3: recall explainer\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md:\n  Line 10: the current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\n\n  Line 24: 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n\n  Line 178: ### 1.5 `memories_fts`\n\n  Line 180: FTS5 external-content virtual table. Shadows `memories.content`. Maintained by three triggers.\n\n  Line 183: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n\n  Line 190:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n\n  Line 193:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n\n  Line 196:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n\n  Line 197:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n\n  Line 201: See §3 for full FTS5 configuration analysis.\n\n  Line 220: | `decay.half_life_days` | integer | Days before a non-recalled memory halves its rank boost |\n\n  Line 256: FROM memories_fts\n\n  Line 257: JOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\n\n  Line 258: WHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n\n  Line 261: ORDER BY memories_fts.rank, m.importance DESC\n\n  Line 265: Hits: `memories_fts` (FTS5 own index), `idx_memories_status`, `idx_memories_project`.\n\n  Line 266: Gap: the `ORDER BY` applies FTS5 BM25 rank then falls back to a table scan for `importance DESC`. A covering index on `(status, project_scope, importance DESC)` would eliminate the table scan for the secondary sort. This is a low-priority improvement since FTS5 already constrains the result set to a small rowid list.\n\n  Line 312: ## 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n\n  Line 317: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n\n  Line 329: ### 3.2 BM25 ranking\n\n\n(Results truncated: showing 100 of 146 matches (46 hidden). Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":146,"truncated":true},"title":"memories_fts|FTS5|bm25|rank|semantic fallback|semanticFallback|explainer|why_ranked|Score formula|0\\.40|0\\.35|0\\.15|0\\.10","time":{"start":1780924936318,"end":1780924936357}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_04b3cfa87004f1e2016a26c208425c8191864e08b5f87e0b4f"}},"id":"prt_ea765f07b001FgfDLL766U5A19","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765cc190019agoUNAu6yQRpq"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780924936850,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"id":"prt_ea765f28e001BKRZiRJ3zGhOtR","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"afb8f0ae2e954a0ab3fc9e39afbfa0122a496efb","messageID":"msg_ea765cc190019agoUNAu6yQRpq","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":60002,"input":12570,"output":287,"reasoning":41,"cache":{"write":0,"read":47104}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780924939280,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"id":"prt_ea765fc0e0014uyCiT3NJjxbYz","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","snapshot":"2a2b345200b923b46bbc477901b78acf27010f0f","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780924947090,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vlYwgCUGdOdwo0F61C5rqe3E","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":300,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n300: `src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n301: \n302: ### 5.1 Tables\n303: \n304: | Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n305: |-------|---------|-----------|\n306: | `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n307: | `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n308: | `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n309: | `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n310: | `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n311: | `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n312: | `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n313: \n314: ### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n315: \n316: | Column | Purpose |\n317: |--------|---------|\n318: | `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n319: | `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n320: | `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n321: | `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n322: | `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n323: | `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n324: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n325: | `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n326: | `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n327: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n328: | `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n329: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n330: \n331: ### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n332: \n333: | Column | Purpose |\n334: |--------|---------|\n335: | `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n336: | `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n337: | `content` | Free text |\n338: | `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n339: | `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n340: | `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n341: \n342: ### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n343: \n344: - `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n345:   Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n346:   insert/update/delete.\n347: - Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n348:   `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n349: - BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n350:   decay factors before returning top-N.\n351: \n352: ### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n353: \n354: The current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n355: \n356: - **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n357: - **Rule sketch:**\n358:   - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n359:   - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n360:     by a decay factor (< 1).\n361:   - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n362: - **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n363:   (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n364: - **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n365:   and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n366: \n367: ### 5.6 Relationships\n368: \n369: ```mermaid\n370: erDiagram\n371:   memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n372:   tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n373:   memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n374:   memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n375:   memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n376:   memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)\n\n(Showing lines 300-379 of 1075. Use offset=380 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n| `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n| `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n| `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n| `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n| `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n\n### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n| `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n| `content` | Free text |\n| `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n| `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n\n### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n\n- `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n  Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n  insert/update/delete.\n- Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n  `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n- BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n  decay factors before returning top-N.\n\n### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n\nThe current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n\n- **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n- **Rule sketch:**\n  - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n  - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n    by a decay factor (< 1).\n  - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n- **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n  (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n- **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n  and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n\n### 5.6 Relationships\n\n```mermaid\nerDiagram\n  memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n  tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n  memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n  memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n  memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n  memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n```\n\n### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)","lineStart":300,"lineEnd":379,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780924947081,"end":1780924947088}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05453df3b44b8688016a26c212f900819b8a11ccfca0a29e9f"}},"id":"prt_ea7661a81001YlrBlyAw0S37hW","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780924947138,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_GiI6AMvLUQsLHada6IiZ3xft","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":472,"limit":40},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n472: ### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n473: \n474: **Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n475: \n476: **Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\n477: memories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\n478: single-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n479: \n480: **Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\n481: returns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n482: `embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\n483: boost, return top-N.\n484: \n485: **Alternatives considered.**\n486: \n487: - **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n488:   (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n489:   (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n490:   keyword-shaped.\n491: - **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n492:   dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n493: - **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n494:   queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n495:   patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n496: - **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n497:   beats raw similarity for natural language.\n498: \n499: **Consequences.**\n500: \n501: - (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n502: - (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n503: - (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n504:   to avoid bloat.\n505: - (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n506:   (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n507: - (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n508: \n509: ---\n510: \n511: ### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n\n(Showing lines 472-511 of 1075. Use offset=512 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n\n**Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n\n**Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\nmemories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\nsingle-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n\n**Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\nreturns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n`embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\nboost, return top-N.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n  (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n  (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n  keyword-shaped.\n- **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n\n**Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n\n**Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\nmemories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\nsingle-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n\n**Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\nreturns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n`embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\nboost, return top-N.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n  (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n  (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n  keyword-shaped.\n- **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n  dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n- **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n  queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n  patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n- **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n  beats raw similarity for natural language.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n- (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n- (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n  to avoid bloat.\n- (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n  (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n- (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n\n---\n\n### ADR-004 — Memory decay model","lineStart":472,"lineEnd":511,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780924947125,"end":1780924947135}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05453df3b44b8688016a26c212f91c819bab08f8a1f7df1d95"}},"id":"prt_ea7661a8b001u4Z13AD568kkQc","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780924947275,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fp4qZUwi9u2teZxTx4zVvoJL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":799,"limit":35},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n799: | C8 | Recall result explainer | trust | G-K |\n800: | C9 | Time-travel replay | retrospectives | G-G |\n801: | C10 | Memory diffing across versions | onboarding | G-B |\n802: \n803: ### 8.3 C1 — Pluggable embedding provider\n804: \n805: Today: single, ad-hoc embedding path. Future: an `EmbeddingProvider` interface\n806: selected at install time. Implementations: `null` (FTS5 only), `local-hash`\n807: (deterministic), `claude-tool` (calls back into Claude Code), `bundled-onnx`\n808: (opt-in, only if the user chooses to install a small model).\n809: \n810: ```mermaid\n811: flowchart LR\n812:   Learn[learn] --> EI[EmbeddingProvider Interface]\n813:   Recall[recall] --> EI\n814:   EI --> P1[null provider]\n815:   EI --> P2[local-hash provider]\n816:   EI --> P3[claude-tool provider]\n817:   EI --> P4[onnx local provider]\n818:   EI -- write/read --> DB[(memory_embeddings table)]\n819: ```\n820: \n821: Recall remains FTS5-first; the embedding step is a fallback **and** an enrichment\n822: (pre-rank pass for high-recall queries). Provider is hot-swappable: changing the\n823: provider triggers a one-time re-embed pass via the janitor.\n824: \n825: ### 8.4 C2 — Multi-device E2E encrypted sync\n826: \n827: The developer should have one memory across machines without trusting any cloud.\n828: \n829: ```mermaid\n830: sequenceDiagram\n831:   participant Laptop\n832:   participant Relay as Sync Relay (zero-knowledge)\n833:   participant Desktop\n\n(Showing lines 799-833 of 1075. Use offset=834 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"| C8 | Recall result explainer | trust | G-K |\n| C9 | Time-travel replay | retrospectives | G-G |\n| C10 | Memory diffing across versions | onboarding | G-B |\n\n### 8.3 C1 — Pluggable embedding provider\n\nToday: single, ad-hoc embedding path. Future: an `EmbeddingProvider` interface\nselected at install time. Implementations: `null` (FTS5 only), `local-hash`\n(deterministic), `claude-tool` (calls back into Claude Code), `bundled-onnx`\n(opt-in, only if the user chooses to install a small model).\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  Learn[learn] --> EI[EmbeddingProvider Interface]\n  Recall[recall] --> EI\n  EI --> P1[null provider]\n  EI --> P2[local-hash provider]\n  EI --> P3[claude-tool provider]\n  EI --> P4[onnx local provider]\n  EI -- write/read --> DB[(memory_embeddings table)]","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"| C8 | Recall result explainer | trust | G-K |\n| C9 | Time-travel replay | retrospectives | G-G |\n| C10 | Memory diffing across versions | onboarding | G-B |\n\n### 8.3 C1 — Pluggable embedding provider\n\nToday: single, ad-hoc embedding path. Future: an `EmbeddingProvider` interface\nselected at install time. Implementations: `null` (FTS5 only), `local-hash`\n(deterministic), `claude-tool` (calls back into Claude Code), `bundled-onnx`\n(opt-in, only if the user chooses to install a small model).\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  Learn[learn] --> EI[EmbeddingProvider Interface]\n  Recall[recall] --> EI\n  EI --> P1[null provider]\n  EI --> P2[local-hash provider]\n  EI --> P3[claude-tool provider]\n  EI --> P4[onnx local provider]\n  EI -- write/read --> DB[(memory_embeddings table)]\n```\n\nRecall remains FTS5-first; the embedding step is a fallback **and** an enrichment\n(pre-rank pass for high-recall queries). Provider is hot-swappable: changing the\nprovider triggers a one-time re-embed pass via the janitor.\n\n### 8.4 C2 — Multi-device E2E encrypted sync\n\nThe developer should have one memory across machines without trusting any cloud.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n  participant Laptop\n  participant Relay as Sync Relay (zero-knowledge)\n  participant Desktop","lineStart":799,"lineEnd":833,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780924947212,"end":1780924947271}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05453df3b44b8688016a26c212f924819ba906f27be94e72d0"}},"id":"prt_ea7661ab6001RiWPHfbsvXRQME","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780924947291,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_h0cMRLYfmftquMifJKxdOjob","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","offset":1,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Configuration\n2: \n3: Configure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n4: \n5: ## LTM options\n6: \n7: ```json\n8: {\n9:   \"ltm\": {\n10:     \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n11:     \"decayEnabled\": true,\n12:     \"injectTopN\": 15,\n13:     \"autoRelate\": true,\n14:     \"graphReasoning\": false,\n15:     \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n16:     \"semanticFallback\": true\n17:   }\n18: }\n19: ```\n20: \n21: | Key | Default | Description |\n22: |-----|---------|-------------|\n23: | `dbPath` | auto-resolved | Override db location (prefer `LTM_DB_PATH` env var) |\n24: | `decayEnabled` | `true` | Enable memory relevance decay over time |\n25: | `injectTopN` | `15` | Max memories to inject at SessionStart |\n26: | `autoRelate` | `true` | Automatically link related memories |\n27: | `graphReasoning` | `false` | Enable graph-based reasoning during recall |\n28: | `evaluateSessionLlm` | `false` | Use LLM to evaluate sessions (costs tokens) |\n29: | `semanticFallback` | `true` | Fall back to embedding search when FTS returns no results |\n30: \n31: ## DB path\n32: \n33: Three ways to set it (priority order):\n34: \n35: 1. **`LTM_DB_PATH` env var** — set in your shell profile for a permanent override\n36: 2. **`CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA`** — set automatically by the plugin system on marketplace installs\n37: 3. **Default fallback** — `$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db`\n38: \n39: ```bash\n40: # Shell override example\n41: export LTM_DB_PATH=/custom/path/openltm.db\n42: ```\n43: \n44: ## Server options\n45: \n46: ```json\n47: {\n48:   \"server\": {\n49:     \"apiPort\": 7331,\n50:     \"uiPort\": 7332\n\n(Showing lines 1-50 of 91. Use offset=51 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Configuration\n\nConfigure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n\n## LTM options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ltm\": {\n    \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n    \"decayEnabled\": true,\n    \"injectTopN\": 15,\n    \"autoRelate\": true,\n    \"graphReasoning\": false,\n    \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n    \"semanticFallback\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","text":"# Configuration\n\nConfigure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n\n## LTM options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ltm\": {\n    \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n    \"decayEnabled\": true,\n    \"injectTopN\": 15,\n    \"autoRelate\": true,\n    \"graphReasoning\": false,\n    \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n    \"semanticFallback\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n| Key | Default | Description |\n|-----|---------|-------------|\n| `dbPath` | auto-resolved | Override db location (prefer `LTM_DB_PATH` env var) |\n| `decayEnabled` | `true` | Enable memory relevance decay over time |\n| `injectTopN` | `15` | Max memories to inject at SessionStart |\n| `autoRelate` | `true` | Automatically link related memories |\n| `graphReasoning` | `false` | Enable graph-based reasoning during recall |\n| `evaluateSessionLlm` | `false` | Use LLM to evaluate sessions (costs tokens) |\n| `semanticFallback` | `true` | Fall back to embedding search when FTS returns no results |\n\n## DB path\n\nThree ways to set it (priority order):\n\n1. **`LTM_DB_PATH` env var** — set in your shell profile for a permanent override\n2. **`CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA`** — set automatically by the plugin system on marketplace installs\n3. **Default fallback** — `$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db`\n\n```bash\n# Shell override example\nexport LTM_DB_PATH=/custom/path/openltm.db\n```\n\n## Server options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"server\": {\n    \"apiPort\": 7331,\n    \"uiPort\": 7332","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":50,"totalLines":91,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","time":{"start":1780924947250,"end":1780924947285}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05453df3b44b8688016a26c212f930819b8dcc12e2841e47ce"}},"id":"prt_ea7661b2a001QB0Zv7SdMAxWtX","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780924947291,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_D2OunG7kQ6wOO51ABd5ZbZxO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":902,"limit":22},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n902: ### 8.10 C8 — Recall result explainer\n903: \n904: Each result returns a one-line `why_ranked` (e.g. \"FTS5 BM25=4.2 + recency boost +\n905: importance 4 → score 6.7\"). Powers debuggability; the user can teach the system\n906: by adjusting importance instead of guessing.\n907: \n908: ### 8.11 C9 — Time-travel replay\n909: \n910: A `memory_audit` append-only log (W11) plus a `--at <date>` flag on `recall`\n911: allows reconstructing the memory state at any past point. Boot a session as if it\n912: were a month ago: `/openltm:project replay --date 2026-03-15`.\n913: \n914: ### 8.12 C10 — Memory diffing across versions\n915: \n916: Pair to C9. `/openltm:memory diff --from 2026-01-01 --to 2026-04-01` returns\n917: *added*, *forgotten*, *superseded*, *importance-changed* memories between two\n918: points. Surfaces as a markdown report or a graph-app v2 view.\n919: \n920: ### 8.13 The magnificent container picture\n921: \n922: ```mermaid\n923: C4Container\n\n(Showing lines 902-923 of 1075. Use offset=924 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"### 8.10 C8 — Recall result explainer\n\nEach result returns a one-line `why_ranked` (e.g. \"FTS5 BM25=4.2 + recency boost +\nimportance 4 → score 6.7\"). Powers debuggability; the user can teach the system\nby adjusting importance instead of guessing.\n\n### 8.11 C9 — Time-travel replay\n\nA `memory_audit` append-only log (W11) plus a `--at <date>` flag on `recall`\nallows reconstructing the memory state at any past point. Boot a session as if it\nwere a month ago: `/openltm:project replay --date 2026-03-15`.\n\n### 8.12 C10 — Memory diffing across versions\n\nPair to C9. `/openltm:memory diff --from 2026-01-01 --to 2026-04-01` returns\n*added*, *forgotten*, *superseded*, *importance-changed* memories between two\npoints. Surfaces as a markdown report or a graph-app v2 view.\n\n### 8.13 The magnificent container picture\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"### 8.10 C8 — Recall result explainer\n\nEach result returns a one-line `why_ranked` (e.g. \"FTS5 BM25=4.2 + recency boost +\nimportance 4 → score 6.7\"). Powers debuggability; the user can teach the system\nby adjusting importance instead of guessing.\n\n### 8.11 C9 — Time-travel replay\n\nA `memory_audit` append-only log (W11) plus a `--at <date>` flag on `recall`\nallows reconstructing the memory state at any past point. Boot a session as if it\nwere a month ago: `/openltm:project replay --date 2026-03-15`.\n\n### 8.12 C10 — Memory diffing across versions\n\nPair to C9. `/openltm:memory diff --from 2026-01-01 --to 2026-04-01` returns\n*added*, *forgotten*, *superseded*, *importance-changed* memories between two\npoints. Surfaces as a markdown report or a graph-app v2 view.\n\n### 8.13 The magnificent container picture\n\n```mermaid\nC4Container","lineStart":902,"lineEnd":923,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780924947239,"end":1780924947288}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05453df3b44b8688016a26c212f92c819b9610aa1e2f18fadf"}},"id":"prt_ea7661b0d0012MlYIp47Wz2EDA","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea765f3f1001YVvQd4C3R1vN84"}}
