{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925011629,"sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_Q8HLSCQSyo9MN9HspHExYvqV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"RRF|BM25|FTS5|trigger|FSRS|co-activation|causal|explain|rerank|why_ranked|fused vector","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.agents/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 81 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/embedding_resilience.md:\n  Line 66: | Full | Active provider healthy | Vector similarity + keyword + FTS5 |\n\n  Line 68: | Keyword only | All embedding providers failed | FTS5 full-text search + trigger matching |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/embedder_pluggability.md:\n  Line 4: trigger_phrases:\n\n  Line 145: The rescue layer is a runtime-gated stage 2b/3 that hydrates ranked candidates with same-folder siblings, lexical backfill from `memory_index`, and trigger-lane weighting that ignores generic one-token triggers. It is additive to the dense-embedding pipeline; the embedder itself is unchanged.\n\n  Line 147: Path A (cross-encoder reranker) was explicitly rejected — unnecessary for the closure gate and would have added runtime/model complexity. Path B (trigger-lane weighting) and Path C (sibling/backfill rescue) shipped.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/embedder_architecture.md:\n  Line 4: trigger_phrases:\n\n  Line 146: `memory_health` accepts `includeFullReport:true` for byte-aware runtime diagnostics. The extended report includes RSS, V8 heap totals, external memory, ArrayBuffer memory, V8 malloc counters, cache byte estimates for tool cache, trigger matcher regex retention, and the in-process embedding LRU.\n\n  Line 158: The MCP server now starts with a thin bootstrap: tool schemas, validation, runtime detection, signal handlers, and stdio binding are registered immediately, while the memory runtime initializes on first memory-owning tool call. `ensureMemoryRuntimeInitialized(reason)` guards DB open, integrity and dimension checks, storage/search consumer init, BM25 warmup, reindex resume, retry manager startup, and the background scan.\n\n  Line 162: The trade-off is first-call latency: the first `memory_search`, `memory_context`, `memory_save`, embedder, checkpoint, ingest, eval, causal, or session-learning call pays the runtime initialization cost. Idle startup stays smaller because SQLite, BM25, retry jobs, startup scans, and local model sidecars remain cold until memory is actually used.\n\n  Line 166: Only the model-based cross-encoder reranker was removed: `mcp_server/lib/search/cross-encoder.ts` is gone and the local rerank sidecar skill was deleted (cloud rerankers were removed earlier). Stage 3 itself is NOT gone — `mcp_server/lib/search/pipeline/stage3-rerank.ts` still runs algorithmic MMR diversity pruning (gated by `SPECKIT_MMR`) and MPAB chunk-collapse over the fused vector/BM25/FTS/graph/degree results. The retired A/B benchmark (`mcp_server/benchmarks/benchmark-2026-05-20-rerank-ab/`) had already kept the cross-encoder out of the default config (negligible hit-rate gain, large p95 latency regression) and is retained only as a historical record.\n\n  Line 170: `SPECKIT_BM25_ENGINE` controls the lexical BM25 provider without changing the public `bm25Search()` API. The default `auto` mode uses SQLite FTS5 when the canonical database has `memory_fts`, so startup skips the resident JavaScript BM25 warmup and the BM25 lane is populated from FTS5 results tagged as `bm25` for compatibility with keyword fusion.\n\n  Line 172: Use `SPECKIT_BM25_ENGINE=legacy-inmemory` to restore the old warm JavaScript singleton for tokenizer, stemmer, or rollback investigations. `SPECKIT_BM25_ENGINE=sqlite` forces FTS5 only and fails clearly when `memory_fts` is missing. `packed-inmemory` is reserved for a future packed term-id implementation and currently warns before falling back to legacy in-memory behavior.\n\n  Line 174: The lexical normalizer lives in `mcp_server/lib/search/lexical-normalizer.ts` and is shared by both BM25 paths. It remains the source of truth for query synonyms, lightweight stemming, FTS-safe query expansion, and BM25 query tokens, so switching the rank provider does not silently drop synonym recall.\n\n  Line 196: `SPECKIT_CONTEXT_SERVER_MAX_OLD_SPACE_MB` can pass `--max-old-space-size=<mb>` to the spawned `context-server.js` child for profiling or leak-canary sessions. Leave it unset for normal operation until packed BM25 and byte-bounded cache packets have reduced retained heap enough to pick a safe cap.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/trigger_config.md:\n  Line 3: description: Complete configuration guide for memory trigger phrases and the fast trigger matching system.\n\n  Line 8: Complete configuration guide for memory trigger phrases and the fast trigger matching system.\n\n  Line 20: > **OpenCode Note:** Automatic interval-based saves (e.g., \"every 20 messages\") are NOT supported in OpenCode because OpenCode lacks the hooks system required to count messages and trigger saves automatically. All context preservation must be manually triggered.\n\n  Line 22: This reference covers trigger phrase configuration, the MCP-based matching system, and best practices for custom trigger design.\n\n  Line 28: | `/memory:save` Command | Primary save trigger | Immediate |\n\n  Line 31: | Custom Config | Project-specific triggers | Configurable |\n\n  Line 81: The `memory_match_triggers` MCP tool provides fast trigger phrase matching without requiring embeddings:\n\n  Line 84: // Fast trigger matching (<50ms) - no embeddings required\n\n  Line 85: const result = await mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_match_triggers({\n\n  Line 90: // Returns matching spec-doc records based on trigger phrases\n\n  Line 101: The constitutional memory for Gate 3 enforcement uses 33 trigger phrases to detect file modification intent:\n\n  Line 116: 1. AI calls `memory_match_triggers({ prompt: \"user message\" })`\n\n  Line 117: 2. If prompt matches any Gate 3 trigger, constitutional memory surfaces\n\n  Line 124: const matches = await memory_match_triggers({\n\n  Line 139: | **Test coverage** | Verify triggers match common user phrases |\n\n  Line 140: | **Limit count** | 20-40 triggers recommended for constitutional memories |\n\n  Line 146: Beyond the default trigger phrases, the system recognizes expanded signal types for contextual trigger matching:\n\n  Line 154: These signals are detected during `memory_match_triggers()` processing and influence save-time arbitration (prediction-error scoring) and correction tracking.\n\n  Line 158: Save-time trigger validation now applies sanitization rules to prevent low-quality triggers from degrading retrieval precision:\n\n  Line 162: | **Single-word filter** | Overly generic single-word triggers (e.g., \"code\", \"fix\", \"error\") are stripped during save-time validation to reduce false-positive surfacing |\n\n  Line 163: | **Duplicate detection** | Triggers that duplicate existing constitutional or high-importance memory triggers are flagged and removed |\n\n  Line 165: | **Stopword filter** | Common stopwords used alone as triggers are rejected |\n\n  Line 167: **Post-save quality review** checks trigger_phrases in the saved memory and reports HIGH-severity issues when triggers are overly broad or likely to cause false matches. The AI must patch these manually via Edit tool when flagged.\n\n  Line 170: - `memory_match_triggers()` now applies a relevance threshold before returning matches, reducing noise from weak partial matches\n\n  Line 171: - Trigger matching respects importance tier: constitutional triggers always match, while normal-tier triggers require higher confidence scores\n\n  Line 172: - When multiple memories match the same trigger, results are deduplicated by content similarity (>=0.88 threshold)\n\n  Line 221:     \"triggers\": {\n\n  Line 222:       // Add custom trigger phrases\n\n  Line 225:         \"another trigger\",\n\n  Line 229:       // Disable default triggers (optional)\n\n  Line 242: // Extended detection with custom triggers\n\n  Line 250:   'another trigger',\n\n  Line 257:   // Check default triggers first\n\n  Line 262:   // Check custom triggers\n\n  Line 293: | Custom trigger check | <20ms | <50ms | >100ms |\n\n  Line 298: // Pre-compile regex for frequently-used triggers\n\n  Line 363: Before deploying custom triggers:\n\n  Line 365: - [ ] Test trigger phrases don't conflict with common conversation\n\n  Line 367: - [ ] Document custom triggers in project README\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/save_workflow.md:\n  Line 34: | **Slash Command** | Yes               | Interactive saves, manual triggers | Low    | ~200       |\n\n  Line 136: /memory:search  # Unified retrieval + analysis: search, epistemic baselines, causal graph, evaluation\n\n  Line 543: | **HIGH** | MUST manually patch via Edit tool (fix title, trigger_phrases, importance_tier) |\n\n  Line 550: - Overly broad `trigger_phrases` that cause false-positive surfacing\n\n  Line 557: - Trigger phrase sanitization strips overly generic single-word triggers during save-time validation\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/memory_system.md:\n  Line 25: | Database | `mcp_server/database/context-index__*.sqlite` | SQLite with FTS5 + vector embeddings; active profile filename resolved by `shared/embeddings/profile.ts:resolveActiveProfileDbPath` |\n\n  Line 58: 5. `createSpecDocumentChain()` links lifecycle docs for causal traversal\n\n  Line 108: | L2: Core | `memory_match_triggers()` | Fast keyword matching (<50ms) with cognitive features | Gate enforcement |\n\n  Line 109: | L2: Core | `memory_save()` | Index a saved continuity artifact or spec doc. Re-generates embedding when **content hash** changes. Title-only changes do not trigger re-embedding. | After generate-context.js |\n\n  Line 115: | L4: Mutation | `memory_update()` | Update memory metadata (title, tier, triggers) | Correct memory properties |\n\n  Line 124: | L6: Analysis | `memory_drift_why()` | Trace causal chain for a spec-doc record (\"why was this decided?\") | Understand decision lineage |\n\n  Line 125: | L6: Analysis | `memory_causal_link()` | Create causal relationship between two memories | Link decision to its cause |\n\n  Line 126: | L6: Analysis | `memory_causal_stats()` | Get statistics about the causal memory graph | Check causal coverage |\n\n  Line 392: ### Model B: FSRS Power-Law Retrievability\n\n  Line 396: Used for composite scoring and the 5-state model (Section 10). Based on the FSRS v4 spaced-repetition formula:\n\n  Line 398: **Formula:** `R = (1 + FSRS_FACTOR × t/S)^(-0.5)`\n\n  Line 404: - `FSRS_FACTOR` = `19/81 ≈ 0.235` (in composite-scoring) or `1/19` inline fallback (in attention-decay)\n\n  Line 407: The FSRS model produces a power-law curve (slower initial decay, steeper long-term decay) compared to the exponential Model A. It is used by `calculateRetrievabilityScore()` in composite scoring and by the tier classifier for state transitions.\n\n  Line 474: - Matched via trigger phrases for fast keyword matching\n\n  Line 480: 2. Add YAML frontmatter with triggers:\n\n  Line 484:    triggers:\n\n  Line 562: **Note:** There is no content normalization (lowercasing, whitespace/date normalization) in the hashing pipeline. Hashes are computed on raw content, so even whitespace-only changes will produce a different hash and trigger re-indexing.\n\n  Line 612: The richer `classifyTier()` function wraps this with half-life support, pinned-memory handling, and constitutional/critical exemptions. It computes retrievability using the FSRS formula (see Section 6, Model B) with an effective stability derived from the spec-doc record's type-specific half-life.\n\n  Line 627: Each spec-doc record type has a configured half-life (in days). This is converted to FSRS stability:\n\n  Line 633: The effective stability is `max(fsrs_stability, type_stability)`, ensuring new spec-doc records benefit from their type's baseline while well-reviewed memories keep earned FSRS stability.\n\n  Line 639: | FSRS review (access) | Increases stability → higher R → may promote state |\n\n  Line 640: | Time passes without access | R decays via FSRS formula → may demote state |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/epistemic_vectors.md:\n  Line 296: 3. Would I be comfortable explaining all decisions made?\n","metadata":{"matches":81,"truncated":false},"title":"RRF|BM25|FTS5|trigger|FSRS|co-activation|causal|explain|rerank|why_ranked|fused vector","time":{"start":1780925011609,"end":1780925011626}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e68cd3eda11ad55016a26c25377488191b6477748fb21bd38"}},"id":"prt_ea767164f001SwChZX2j0zs73A","sessionID":"ses_1589b1327ffe3NF41ZJpTNBQ7B","messageID":"msg_ea766f2770013tqKSAdnoVB8sd"}}
